article.description:
Don't expect Antoine Walker to take pity on the
Knicks just because Boston has beaten them eight times in a row.
article.headline: Celtics sweep Knicks for second straight year
article.linkText: Same old story: Celtics continue mastery of Knicks
article.story:
BOSTON (AP) -- Don't expect Antoine Walker to take pity on the Knicks just because Boston has beaten them eight times in a row.
 
Walker
"I used to be on the other end," Walker said after scoring 34 points to help the Celtics continue their mastery of New York with a 97-95 victory Wednesday night. Paul Pierce scored 24, and Tony Battie blocked the potential game-tying shot with 1.1 seconds left as the Celtics wrapped up their second consecutive season sweep of the Knicks. That hasn't happened since Boston won 19 straight from 1965-67. It's a complete reversal from when Walker came into the league in 1996. The Knicks won 21 in a row against the Celtics from 1993-98, and Walker remembers it well. "My first couple of years, they dominated us, so I don't have any remorse," Walker said. "I want to put it to them the way they put it to us." Allan Houston scored 22 for New York, and Howard Eisley had 15 points and 10 assists. Latrell Sprewell had 18 points, but he was 1-for-9 from 3-point range -- one of them an airball in the final seconds that could have won the game. Clarence Weatherspoon made a great effort to grab the rebound over Battie, but when he put up the potential game-tying shot, Battie swatted it away with his left hand. The final seconds ran off the clock during the scramble for the loose ball, and the Celtics ran onto the court to swarm Battie. "I got the rebound, I tried to stick it back and he blocked it," Weatherspoon said. "What more can I say?" The Celtics led by as many as 12 points in the third and were ahead 74-66 in the final minute of the quarter. But New York scored the next six points to make it 74-72, then stayed close before tying it 92-all with 2:00 left after five straight points from Kurt Thomas. Walker followed with a 3-pointer from the right side to give Boston the lead. The Celtics never trailed again, but the Knicks made them sweat. Sprewell missed a 3-pointer with Eric Williams in his face, and Battie grabbed the rebound. Pierce made one of two free throws, then Houston hit a 3-pointer with 50 seconds left to cut the deficit to one point. Walker missed a shovel shot, and New York called timeout with 26.6 seconds left. With 12.8 seconds left, Houston drove the lane and pulled up for a 10-footer. Battie almost tipped it in, but then got fouled by Thomas pulling down the rebound. He missed the first free throw but made the second to give Boston a 97-95 lead. Game notes
Patriots coach Bill Belichick attended and got the biggest cheer of the night when he was shown on the scoreboard. ... Walker had 23 points at the half. ... Celtics rookie J.R. Bremer went to St. Bonaventure, which chose to boycott its last two games to protest sanctions for using an ineligible player. Bremer said he was only aware of the developments by following it on the news, but his Web site www.jrbremer.com, has gone from 2,000 to almost 15,000 hits because of the story. ... Houston came into the game averaging 23 points against the Celtics this season.
